03910nmm a2200565Ia 9780520923201DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231997cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209232017 a10.1525/97805209232012doi  a(DE-B1597)542805  a(OCoLC)1163878777  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aARC0050002bisacsh1 aBanham, Reyner, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Critic Writes :bSelected Essays by Reyner Banham /cReyner Banham; ed. by Mary Banham, Sutherland Lyall, Paul Barker, Cedric Price.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (366 p.) :b1 frontisp.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew twentieth-century writers on architecture and design have enjoyed the renown of Reyner Banham. Born and trained in England and a U.S. resident starting in 1976, Banham wrote incisively about American and European buildings and culture. Now readers can enjoy a chronological cross-section of essays, polemics, and reviews drawn from more than three decades of Banham's writings.The volume, which includes discussions of Italian Futurism, Adolf Loos, Paul Scheerbart, and the Bauhaus as well as explorations of contemporary architecture by Frank Gehry, James Stirling, and Norman Foster, conveys the full range of Banham's belief in industrial and technological development as the motor of architectural evolution. Banham's interests and passions ranged from architecture and the culture of pop art to urban and industrial design. In brilliant analyses of automobile styling, mobile homes, science fiction films, and the American predilection for gadgets, he anticipated many of the preoccupations of contemporary cultural studies. Los Angeles, the city that Banham commemorated in a book and a film, receives extensive attention in essays on the Santa Monica Pier, the Getty Museum, Forest Lawn cemetery, and the ubiquitous freeway system.Eminently readable, provocative, and entertaining, this book is certain to consolidate Banham's reputation among architects and students of contemporary culture. For those acquainted with his writing, it offers welcome surprises as well as familiar delights. For those encountering Banham for the first time, it comprises the perfect introduction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecture. 0aArt. 0aDesignxHistoryx20th century. 0aDesignxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Art). 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh1 aBanham, Mary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarker, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLyall, Sutherland, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPrice, Cedric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520923201?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520923201423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520923201/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles